# =============================================
# General Settings
# =============================================

ROUND_2 = True
# If False, makes predictions for Sep 1 - 26 using data through Aug 31
# If True, makes predictions for Nov 23 - Dec 13 using data through Dec 6

PRODUCE_SUBMISSION = True
# Leave off when testing as not to spam submission folder with junk

HYPERPARAMETERS = [(1, 1, 0), [3, 1, 0, 7], "n"]
# The hyperparameters for the SARIMAX model. 
# Should be in the format ((p, d, q), (P, D, Q, S), TREND.

# The first tuple is for daily changes in cases.
# The second tuple is for weekly ("seasonal") variations. 
# TREND is set to "n" (none) as the model overfits badly with any other setting

# p - How many days or weeks to look back; equivalent to lag order
# d - How many times to difference the series. Effectively uses the discrete dth derivative
# q - How much to smooth each series using a q-day or q-week moving average
# S should always be 7 -- a week is 7 days and there are clear weekly trends in the data.

# Best submission uses: ((1, 1, 0), (3, 1, 0, 7), "n")

# =============================================
# Experimental features used by best submission
# =============================================

USE_CONFIRMED_TO_PREDICT_DEATHS = True
WEEKS_BACK = 3
# The X in SARIMAX stands for "eXogenous", which means we can use it as bootleg VAR.
  # However, we have to do the shifting manually.
  # This setting passes Confirmed as an exogenous variable for deaths. 

USE_MOBILITY_DATA = True
WEEKS_BACK_MOBILITY = 2
GRANGER_CUTOFF = 0.02
GRANGER_CUTOFF_DEATHS = 0.2
# Uses mobility to predict Confirmed
# Performs a granger test and only uses mobility if p-value < CUTOFF
MOBILITY_TRANSFORMS = ('Mobility3', '')

BEST_TRANSFORM_DICT = {}
# Global debug variable
for transform in MOBILITY_TRANSFORMS:
  BEST_TRANSFORM_DICT[transform] = []

TRY_DIFFERENT_LAGS = False

PLOT_MOBILITY = False
# Debug

LINEAR_SHIFT_INTERPOLATE = False
# If true, uses a linear interpolation after shifting 
# If false, uses a backwards fill of 0 

# =============================================
# Experimental features not used by best submission 
# These either suck or are untested
# =============================================

USE_HOSPITALIZATIONS_TO_PREDICT_DEATHS = False
WEEKS_BACK_HOSPITALIZATIONS = 2 
# Lags hospitalizations by the same amount as Confirmed, then feeds them to deaths predictor.
  # The main issue with this approach is that the predictions for hospitalizations
  # don't use Confirmed, so they're often awry.

  # Bigger issue: there is no hospitalization data in round 2...

# Fit multiple SARIMAX models, then choose the one with the lowest AIC
COMPARE_MODELS_USING_AIC = False
ALTPARAMS = ((1, 1, 0), (1, 1, 0, 7), "ct")

# Iteratively try a bunch of lag orders, then select the "best" one
# AIC doesn't correspond very well to test error, so this makes some bad decisions
PICK_LAG_ORDERS_USING_AIC = False
MAX_LAG_NONSEASONAL = 20
MAX_LAG_SEASONAL = 4

# Uses a third-party library that searches for the best SARIMA hyperparameters
# Performs better than my implementations, but still picks questionable models
USE_AUTO_ARIMA = False

  df = pd.read_csv('train.csv')
  graph = pd.read_csv('graph.csv')
  dates = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])
  days_since_start = (dates - dates.min()).dt.days
  df.insert(loc=1, column='Day', value=days_since_start)
  df = df.drop(['Date'], axis=1)
  train_start = dates.min()
  train_end = dates.max()
  print(f"Training data starts at {train_start}, ends at {train_end}")

grouped = df.groupby("Province_State")
states_interp = []
for name, group in grouped:
  poly_order = 5
  while 1:
    try:
      group = group.interpolate(method="polynomial", order=poly_order).ffill().bfill()
      break
    except ValueError:
      # Polynomial interpolation of degree N doesn't work if there are not N different points
      poly_order -= 1
      if poly_order == -1:
        raise ValueError
  states_interp.append(group)
df = pd.concat(states_interp, axis=0) 
df = df.ffill().bfill()

states = df['Province_State'].unique().tolist()
state_data = {}
for state in states:
  state_data[state] = df[df['Province_State'] == state].copy()
assert(list(state_data.keys()) == states) #sanity check

# =============================================
# SARIMAX Model
# =============================================

from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import grangercausalitytests

def printModelInfo(state, model_fitted_single_diff, diff_name):
  """ Debug function. Prints most of the goodness measures in the model results.
  Useful to check if there is some measure that is very high or low when there
  are obviously terrible models."""
  print(state, diff_name, "measures - aic:", model_fitted_single_diff.aic, 
          "aicc:", model_fitted_single_diff.aicc, 
          "bic:", model_fitted_single_diff.bic,
          "hqic:", model_fitted_single_diff.hqic, 
          "mae:", model_fitted_single_diff.mae,
          "mse:", model_fitted_single_diff.mse,
          "llf:", model_fitted_single_diff.llf,
          "mean BSE:", np.mean(model_fitted_single_diff.bse))
  
def shiftColumn(df, state, name, steps, forecast=pd.DataFrame(), interpolate=LINEAR_SHIFT_INTERPOLATE, 
                adjustment=(1/50), verbose=False, lag=None):
    """Returns two shifted versions of the given column.
    The first (prior to WEEKS_BACK weeks) is given for SARIMAX to train.
    The second (WEEKS_BACK most recent weeks) is given for SARIMAX to use to make predictions. 
    Arguments:
    df -- A dataframe containing at least the data for the column to shift.
    state -- Name of the state whose data we are shifting. 
    name -- A string giving which column to shift.
    steps -- Number of days we are predicting
    forecast -- Predictions for the column beyond the range of name. 
    interpolate -- Uses linear interpolation instead of filling NAs with 0.
    adjustment -- Multiplies value of column by this number.
    verbose -- Prints shifted column given to SARIMAX for predictions (Debug)
    
    TODO: If forecast is none, this function should create forecast itself."""
    #adjust_forecast_indexes = True
    global WEEKS_BACK
    weeks_back_original = WEEKS_BACK
    weeks_back_difference = 0
    if name not in MOBILITY_TRANSFORMS:
      data = df[df['Province_State'] == state]
    else:
      # mobility data has different state groupings
      data = df
    if forecast.empty:
      #adjust_forecast_indexes = False
      if lag:
        WEEKS_BACK = int(lag / 7)
        weeks_back_difference = 350 * (weeks_back_original - int(lag/7))
      elif name == "People_Hospitalized":
          data[name] = data[name].cumsum()
          if verbose:
            print("Hosp original:", data[name])
          WEEKS_BACK = WEEKS_BACK_HOSPITALIZATIONS
          weeks_back_difference = 350 * (weeks_back_original - WEEKS_BACK_HOSPITALIZATIONS)
      elif name in MOBILITY_TRANSFORMS:
        WEEKS_BACK = WEEKS_BACK_MOBILITY
        weeks_back_difference = 350 * (weeks_back_original - WEEKS_BACK_MOBILITY)
      model = SARIMAX(data[name], order=HYPERPARAMETERS[0], seasonal_order=HYPERPARAMETERS[1],  trend=HYPERPARAMETERS[2])
      # TODO: Allow "exog chaining" (use all previously predicted columns to generate predictions for other columns)
      try:
        model_fitted = model.fit()
      except np.linalg.LinAlgError:
        # It broke SARIMAX. Bad data column
        return None, None
      forecast = model_fitted.forecast(steps)
      if verbose:
        print("Hosp forecast:", forecast)
    forecast = forecast.rename(name)
    exog = data[name].shift(periods=7*WEEKS_BACK) * adjustment
    if interpolate:
      exog = exog.interpolate(method='linear', limit=30, limit_direction='backward')
    else:
      exog = exog.fillna(0)
    # Using linear interpolation / backwards fill here slightly increases error
    if WEEKS_BACK * 7 - steps <= 0:
      #if adjust_forecast_indexes:
      forecast = pd.DataFrame(forecast).set_index(forecast.index * 50 +
                                                                  exog.index[0] - weeks_back_difference).squeeze()
      #else:
        #forecast = pd.DataFrame(forecast).set_index(forecast.index + 1300).squeeze()
      exog_forecast = pd.DataFrame(data[name]).set_index(data[name].index - weeks_back_difference).squeeze().append(forecast)
      exog_forecast = exog_forecast[-(WEEKS_BACK*7+steps):-(WEEKS_BACK*7)] * adjustment
    else:
      exog_forecast = data[name][-(WEEKS_BACK*7):-(WEEKS_BACK*7 - steps)] * adjustment
    if verbose:
      print("Full exog forecast:", exog_forecast) 
    WEEKS_BACK = weeks_back_original
    return exog, exog_forecast

def getForecastSARIMAX(df, state, cols_excluded, steps, confirm_forecast=None):
  """ Performs a SARIMAX regression on df and returns a forecast. 
  Arguments: 
  df -- A dataframe containing at least the data for the state.
  state -- State to perform regression on.
  cols_excluded -- If Deaths is in this list, regresses confirmed. 
  steps -- The number of days to forecast from the last day in df.
  confirm_forecast -- Result of a previous forecast for Confirmed; only used if 
    we are forecasting Deaths and using Confirmed as an exogenous variable.
  """
  global BEST_TRANSFORM_DICT
  original = df[df['Province_State'] == state].drop(cols_excluded, axis=1)
  exog = None
  exog_forecast = None
  if "Deaths" in cols_excluded:
    col = "Confirmed"
    if USE_MOBILITY_DATA:
      graph_col = pd.DataFrame(graph[state + "," + state])
      graph_col.rename(columns={state + "," + state: "Mobility"}, inplace=True)
      graph_col = graph_col.set_index(graph_col.index * 50 + df.index[0])
      #graph_col = graph_col.cumsum()
      print(graph_col)
      df = pd.concat((df, graph_col), axis=1)
      df.info()
      # This one is very bad with Kansas but good in a lot of other places
      #df['Mobility'] = df['Mobility'] / 100000 * df['Confirmed']
      #print("Diff interpolated", df['Confirmed'].diff().interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward'))
      #print("Summed", df['Confirmed'].diff().interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward').rolling(7).sum().interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward'))
      df['Mobility_Original'] = df['Mobility']
      print("The raw mobility data is:", df['Mobility'])
      df['Mobility'] = df['Mobility'] - 0.9 * df['Mobility'].min()
      df['Mobility_Squared'] = df['Mobility'] * df['Mobility'] / 100000000 #* df['Confirmed'].diff().interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward')
      df['Mobility2'] = df['Mobility_Original'] * df['Confirmed'].diff(14).interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward')
      df['Mobility_Exponential'] = np.power(1.00001, df['Mobility_Original'])
      df['Mobility_Exponential'] = df['Mobility_Exponential'].cumsum()
      df['Mobility'] = df['Mobility'].cumsum()
      df['Mobility2'] = df['Mobility2'].cumsum()
      df['Mobility_Original'] = df['Mobility_Original'].cumsum()
      df['Mobility3'] = df['Mobility_Original'] / 100000 * df['Confirmed']
      df['Mobility4'] = df['Mobility'] / 100000 * df['Confirmed']
      df['Mobility5'] = df['Mobility'] * df['Confirmed'].diff(14).interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward')
      df['Mobility7'] = np.power(df['Mobility'] * df['Confirmed'].diff(14).interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward'), 0.5)
      df['Mobility_Exponential_2'] = np.power(df['Mobility_Exponential'] * df['Confirmed'].diff(14).interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward'), 0.5)
      df['Mobility8'] = np.power(df['Mobility'] * df['Confirmed'].diff(14).interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward'), 0.333)
      df['Mobility10'] = (df['Mobility5'].rolling(21).sum().interpolate(method='linear', limit=60, limit_direction='backward') / 100000000).cumsum()
      if PLOT_MOBILITY:
        for transform in MOBILITY_TRANSFORMS:
          df[transform].plot(legend=True)
      print("Mobility data for", state, "\n", df['Mobility'])

      best_transform = None
      min_pvalue = 1
      for mobility_transform in MOBILITY_TRANSFORMS:
        if not mobility_transform:
          continue
        granger_pvalue_mobility = grangercausalitytests(df[df["Province_State"] == state][[col, mobility_transform]],
                                    maxlag=[WEEKS_BACK_MOBILITY*7], verbose=False)[WEEKS_BACK_MOBILITY*7][0]['ssr_ftest'][1]
        if granger_pvalue_mobility < GRANGER_CUTOFF and granger_pvalue_mobility < min_pvalue:
          best_transform = mobility_transform
          min_pvalue = granger_pvalue_mobility
        # Can try different lags here
      print(state, "Granger p_value for mobility data", min_pvalue, "Best transform was ", best_transform)
      lag = None
      if best_transform:
        if TRY_DIFFERENT_LAGS:
          lags = [7 * i + 7 for i in range(WEEKS_BACK_MOBILITY)]
          best_lag = WEEKS_BACK_MOBILITY
          min_pvalue_lags = 1
          for lag in lags:
            granger_pvalue_mobility = grangercausalitytests(df[df["Province_State"] == state][[col, best_transform]],
                                    maxlag=lag, verbose=False)[lag][0]['ssr_ftest'][1]
            if granger_pvalue_mobility < min_pvalue_lags:
              min_pvalue_lags = granger_pvalue_mobility
              best_lag = lag
              print("Best lag for state is ", lag)
        BEST_TRANSFORM_DICT[best_transform].append(state)
        exog, exog_forecast = shiftColumn(df, state, best_transform, steps, lag=lag)
  else:
    col = "Deaths"
    if USE_CONFIRMED_TO_PREDICT_DEATHS:
        print("Granger score for ", state, grangercausalitytests(df[df["Province_State"] == state][[col, "Confirmed"]],
                                    maxlag=WEEKS_BACK*7, verbose=False)[WEEKS_BACK*7][0]['ssr_ftest'][1])
    if USE_CONFIRMED_TO_PREDICT_DEATHS and grangercausalitytests(df[df["Province_State"] == state][[col, "Confirmed"]],
                                    maxlag=WEEKS_BACK*7, verbose=False)[WEEKS_BACK*7][0]['ssr_ftest'][1] < GRANGER_CUTOFF_DEATHS:
      exog, exog_forecast = shiftColumn(df, state, 'Confirmed', steps, confirm_forecast)
      # Maybe don't use hospitalizations unless we know the data is good (Granger test?)
      if USE_HOSPITALIZATIONS_TO_PREDICT_DEATHS:
        try: 
          granger_pvalue_hospitalizations = grangercausalitytests(df[df["Province_State"] == state][[col, 'People_Hospitalized']],
                                    maxlag=[WEEKS_BACK_HOSPITALIZATIONS*7], verbose=False)[WEEKS_BACK_HOSPITALIZATIONS*7][0]['ssr_ftest'][1]
          #print("Hospitalization p value for ", state, granger_pvalue_hospitalizations)
        except ValueError:
          # Don't use hospitalizations: the column broke the causality test!
          granger_pvalue_hospitalizations = 1
      if USE_HOSPITALIZATIONS_TO_PREDICT_DEATHS and granger_pvalue_hospitalizations < GRANGER_CUTOFF:
        exog_2, exog_forecast_2 = shiftColumn(df, state, 'People_Hospitalized', steps, adjustment=(1/1000))
        exog = pd.concat((exog, exog_2), axis=1)
        #print("Exog forecast:", exog_forecast, "Exog forecast 2:" ,exog_forecast_2)
        exog_forecast = pd.concat((exog_forecast, exog_forecast_2), axis=1)
      #print(exog, exog_forecast)
  data = original.copy()
  # Input data for forecasting
  # Forecast
  if USE_AUTO_ARIMA:
    pass
  else:
    model = SARIMAX(data[col], order=HYPERPARAMETERS[0], seasonal_order=HYPERPARAMETERS[1],  trend=HYPERPARAMETERS[2], exog=exog)
    model_fitted = model.fit()
  if COMPARE_MODELS_USING_AIC:
    model_alternate = SARIMAX(data[col], order=ALTPARAMS[0], seasonal_order=ALTPARAMS[1],  trend=ALTPARAMS[2])
    model_alternate_fitted = model_alternate.fit()
    printModelInfo(state, model_fitted, "normal")
    printModelInfo(state, model_alternate_fitted, "alternate")
    #print(model_fitted.mse, model_alternate_fitted.mse)
    if model_fitted.mse > model_alternate_fitted.mse:
      model_fitted = model_alternate_fitted
  elif PICK_LAG_ORDERS_USING_AIC:
    for i in range(MAX_LAG_NONSEASONAL):
      for j in range(MAX_LAG_SEASONAL):
        if i > 6 and j > 0:
          # Seasonality doesn't work with a non-seasonal lag order > season length
          continue
        order = (i, HYPERPARAMETERS[0][1], HYPERPARAMETERS[0][2])
        seasonal_order = (j, HYPERPARAMETERS[1][1], HYPERPARAMETERS[1][2], HYPERPARAMETERS[1][3])
        model_alternate = SARIMAX(data[col], order=order, seasonal_order=seasonal_order,  trend=HYPERPARAMETERS[2])
        try:
          model_alternate_fitted = model_alternate.fit()
        except (ValueError, np.linalg.LinAlgError) as e:
          # Very high lag orders produce non-invertible matrices sometimes
          # Throw away these fits
          continue
        #printModelInfo(state, model_fitted, "single")
        #printModelInfo(state, model_fitted_double_diff, "double")
        if model_fitted.mse > model_alternate_fitted.mse:
          model_fitted = model_alternate_fitted
  if USE_AUTO_ARIMA:
    fc = model_fitted.predict(steps)
  else:
    fc = model_fitted.forecast(steps, exog=exog_forecast)
  # Compile forecast into dataframe
  df_fc = pd.DataFrame(fc)
  # Force forecasts to be monotonically increasing
  df_fc[str(col)+'_forecast'] = np.maximum.accumulate(df_fc)
  print(state, "completed")
  return df_fc.filter(regex='.*_forecast')
